snippet.textDisplay: Pretty decent beginner chili recipe, but you can vastly improve the flavor while also reducing the amount of work you have to do with two tiny tweaks. First, put the spices, salt, and sugar in while you're frying the onions. The oil in the pan will pick up the oils in the spices that carry the actual flavor and bring it throughout the whole dish much more effectively than after the tomatoes come in, because all the water in the tomato keeps the oils from mingling and exchanging flavors as effectively. Second, there's no need to brown the beef in its own pan. Put it in after you caramelize the onions and spices and the fat in the beef will do the same thing the olive oil did with the spices. Otherwise you lose your chance to flavor the meat itself. Plus, bonus, you don't have to wash an extra pan.
snippet.textOriginal: Pretty decent beginner chili recipe, but you can vastly improve the flavor while also reducing the amount of work you have to do with two tiny tweaks. First, put the spices, salt, and sugar in while you're frying the onions. Second, there's no need to brown the beef in its own pan. Put it in after you caramelize the onions and spices and the fat in the beef will do the same thing the olive oil did with the spices.
